In [7]:
lr.predict(np.array([98]).reshape(-1,1))
Out[7]:
array([[24.46707715]])
  • We see that the p-value is very small and hence we can conclude that there is a relationship between the predictor and the response.
  • The relationship between the response and the predictor is quite strong. For every 1000 unit increase in $horsepower$ we observe a 157.8 unit decrease in $mpg$. We also see that $R^{2}$ is 0.606 indicating that about 60% of variability in $mpg$ is removed by the linear regression of $mpg$ onto $horsepower$.
  • The relationship between $mpg$ and $horsepower$ is negative.
  • When $horsepower$ is 98, $mpg$ is 24.467.

  • Here we see that $Urban$ has a very large p-value and hence it is statistically insignificant.
  • $Price$ has a negative coefficient, hence higher the $Price$ lower the $Sales$.
  • $US$ has a positive coefficient, hence if $US = Yes$ then sales will be higher.

We can thus reject the null hypothesis for $US$ and $Price$.

The results obtained from regressing $X$ onto $Y$ is the exact same as regressing $Y$ onto $X$.

$\large\beta = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i}{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2}$

$\large SE(\beta) = \sqrt{\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - x_i \beta)^2}{(n-1) \sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2}}$

$\large t-statistic = \frac{\beta}{SE(\beta)}$

$\large t-statistic = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i^2}$ * $\sqrt{\frac{(n-1) \sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - x_i \beta)^2}}$

$\large t-statistic = \frac{\sqrt{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i y_i}{\sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2} \sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^{n} y_j^2 + \beta^2\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2 - 2\beta\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j y_j}}$

$\large t-statistic = \frac{\sqrt{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i y_i}{\sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2 \sum_{j=1}^{n} y_j^2 + \beta^2(\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2)^2 - 2\beta\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j y_j \sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2}}$

Now lets look at each term on the denominator individuallly:

$\large\beta^2(\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2)^2 = \frac{(\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i)^2}{(\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2)^2}(\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2)^2$

$\large\beta^2(\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2)^2 = (\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i)^2$

$ \large 2\beta\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j y_j \sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2 = 2\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i}{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2} \sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j y_j \sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2$

$ \large 2\beta\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j y_j \sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2 = 2(\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i)^2$

Now the denominator can be simplified to :

$\sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2 \sum_{j=1}^{n} y_j^2 - (\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i)^2}$

Thus,

$\large t-statistic = \frac{\sqrt{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i y_i}{\sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2 \sum_{j=1}^{n} y_j^2 - (\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i)^2}}$

Question 12¶

When we regress $Y$ onto $X$:
$\large\beta = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i}{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2}$

When we regress $X$ onto $Y$:
$\large\beta = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_i y_i}{\sum_{j=1}^{n} y_j^2}$

Thus the coefficients for simple linear regression without an intercept will be equal if $\sum_{j=1}^{n} y_j^2$ equals $\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_j^2$
